<font color="#FF0000">LANGUAGE-VIEW POINT</font><br>
<tt>Sat Feb  1 20:14:56 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To Danny:<br>
     I understand and can accept your point of view.  The Vietnam war is a emotional point for anyone that served and/or lived through it.  Yes, the best way to sum up the war and the things that happened to us there is best described with &quot;colorful language&quot;.  In regards to educating those not there with this language I disagree!!  This is my point of view with what you can call a &quot;bias&quot; as a school teacher.  The language of the time is important to the understanding of the war, its feelings and the era.  This is why I give my students a language course on the war before we get involved in its study.  We cover most terms we used there.  In my personal opinion curses are not part of the education-they alone don't teach anything about the Vietnam war, though terms like &quot;cluster f-ck&quot; and &quot;sh-t happens&quot; certainly do sum it up in a nutshell.  As a writer on Vietnam for magazines, newsletters and school curriculum and lesson plans, I have had to try to get the feelings of the war to the students without using curses.  It can be done and has been done in many excellent records on the war.  In regards to this site, I have accepted and recommended to my school authorities that it not be used as in school as a educational tool.  This has only to do with the &quot;language&quot; used here and how it violates our appropriate media code.  There are ways to capture the feeling of Vietnam. I like to invite fellow vets to our classes to talk about the general feelings and experiences of this war.  No politics-just true gut feelings-no more need be said.  This site can and should be used for all of us ADULTS seeking discussion on the war.  We can exchange our appropriare feelings, not subject to regulation like schools are.  I respect your view Dan and can definitely relate to times when the only appropriate description is not always repeatable in the company of younger children.  I hope you can see my point on the issue, I can defintely see yours.  This is the view point of a person who teaches in our public schools.  Thanks for listening!!!
<p><code>--   (Joe) </code><p>


